I"C<p>This is a brief primer on basic definitions and theorems in measure theory. These important results are from <a href="https://www.amazon.com/Integration-Modern-Analysis-John-Benedetto/dp/0817643060">Integration and Modern Analysis</a>.</p>

<h2 id="definitions">Definitions</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Limit Superior and Limit Inferior</li>
</ul>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">\overline{\lim_{n \to \infty}} x_n \triangleq \inf_n \sup_{k \ge n} x_k</script>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">\underline{\lim_{n \to \infty}} x_n \triangleq \sup_n \inf_{k \ge n} x_k</script>

<ul>
  <li>A <strong>topology</strong> on a set $X$ is a collection $\tau$ of subsets of $X$ having the following properties:
    <ul>
      <li>$\emptyset$ and $X$ are in $\tau$.</li>
      <li>The union of elements of any subcollection of $\tau$ is in $X$.</li>
      <li>The intersection of the elements of any <em>finite</em> subcollection of $\tau$ is in $X$.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>A set $X$ for which topology $\tau$ has been identified is called a <strong> topological space </strong></li>
</ul>
